Now in Logica‚ Vol. ΙΙ7 p. 181, we find this very statement, and at the end of the chapter: Notetur liber tercius Vitulonis (Vitellionis). Ι have not been able to see the work of the Polish optician, but arn inclined to think that it was so well known in Oxford in those days that further reference to it was thought unnecessary. That several of the dicta quoted are rather metaphysical than optical does not militate against this possibility, for all natural philosophers were then meta- physicians. Wyclif cannot be alluding to his own Logica, for the statement mentioned occurs in his Tractatus Tercius. It is true that there he speaks of the third, not the second book of Vitellion, but this may be a mistake of the copyist, or the same details may be found in both books. Further (chap. 111) we shall find the name of the celebrated optician joined to a reference to his book.
